# Harsh "Dummy" Page Breaking Implementation

This plan outlines how to bypass Chrome's smart pagination and force a "dummy" break that literally slices through content (including text lines) at the exact pixel boundary.

## Proposed Changes

### [Component Name] GrapesJS Editor
#### [MODIFY] [BasicsGrapejs-gemini-streaming.jsx](file:///e:/HTMl/docpoilet-ai-all-model-integrations/src/components/Editor/BasicsGrapejs-gemini-streaming.jsx)
- **Refactor [handleExportPDF](file:///e:/HTMl/docpoilet-ai-all-model-integrations/src/components/Editor/BasicsGrapejs-gemini-streaming.jsx#707-773)**:
    - Calculate the required number of pages based on the `pdfPageHeight` and the actual scroll height of the content.
    - Transform the single continuous HTML into a series of "viewport" `div`s.
    - Each viewport will contain the **entire** content shifted vertically using a negative `margin-top`.
    - Apply `overflow: hidden` and fixed `height` to each viewport to force the "dummy" cut.
    - Use `page-break-after: always` to ensure each viewport starts on a new PDF page.

### [Component Name] Playwright API
#### [MODIFY] [route.tsx](file:///e:/HTMl/docpoilet-ai-all-model-integrations/src/app/api/playwright/route.tsx)
- **Relax global styles**: Remove `height: 100% !important` from `html, body` which might restrict multiple pages when using the fragmented approach.
- **Ensure isolation**: Ensure margin resets don't prevent the fragmented pages from correctly aligning to the PDF physical pages.

---

## Verification Plan

### Automated Tests
- I will use the `browser_subagent` to trigger a PDF export and then inspect the resulting [latest_export.html](file:///e:/HTMl/docpoilet-ai-all-model-integrations/src/app/api/playwright/latest_export.html) to verify the multi-page fragmented structure is present.
- I will check that each page wrapper has `overflow: hidden` and the correct `margin-top` shift.

### Manual Verification
- The user should generate a PDF with a long block of text.
- Verify that the text is sliced exactly at the boundary, potentially cutting a line of text in half horizontally between two pages.
